&quot;Monday 7th: Fine bright day in the fournoon. Staid at Genaroux until one O Clock p.m. left there &amp; walked to Murphy's Shanty by way of the Big Dam walked up the creek on the Ice to Longthas Camp. Longtha went to shanty with me &amp; staid overnight it clouded up about 1/2 past two &amp; commenced to snow a little. Staid at Murphys all night.&quot;

&quot;Tuesday 8th: Fine day sun shining but cold. Staid at Murphy's all day L. Birket there to weigh potatoes for Page &amp; Co. but thought it to cold to open the pit. Most of the men did not work. Remie Longtha staid over night. Bought order from James Murphy in favour of Michael Connor against Rathbun &amp; Son for $2.00 for $1.50 cash. Wrote a letter to E. Murphy and sent it to be maild by D. McElroy. Sent one pair of Boots to be left at J. Mellons by McElroy for M. Connors.&quot;

&quot;Wednesday 9th: Dark day, snowed all the four noon &amp; until about 1 O Clock. Cleard off with cold high wind. Butter &amp; Aylsworth came to murphys shanty about 10 O Clock with Welsh.&quot;

Part of Denis Nealon's diary.
